Aqueous Ammonia System

Sweetwater Authority personnel inspect the system on a daily basis, taking note of unusual conditions in any portion of the system.  In the event of an emergency on the aqueous ammonia system, authorized staff will attempt to isolate the cause of the emergency by shutting off the feed pumps and notifying management and the in-house HazMat Team, as necessary.  Emergency agencies will also be notified as necessary.

F. Planned Changes to Improve Safety

Chlorine System

In September 1994, the chlorine system was thoroughly examined for safety hazards by way of a Process Hazard Analysis (PHA).  In addition, PHA Revalidations were conducted in March 1999, June 2004, and February 2009. The 2009 PHA Revalidation consisted of:

1.  A review of the PHA Requirements / History (Overview / Training Session);
2.  A detailed review of the recommended action items from the 1995 Initial Process Hazard Analysis, 1999 PHA Revalidation Study, and 2004 PHA Revalidation Study; 
3.  An equipment list review;
4.  A detailed review of any changes to the chlorine system since the 2004 study (reviewed Management of Change Records);
5.  A discussion of any releases of chlorine since the 2004 study (review of Incident Investigation Records);
6.  Development of HAZOP log sheets;
7.  Completion of Emergency Response, Chlorine Checklist, Chlorine What-If Questions, and External Events checklists; and
8.  A facility inspection.

